Spell selection
===============

   For each human wizard in turn, the right of the screen is filled
with the currently available spells for that wizard. Information can be
obtained about the spells by reading about the spells in this manual or
by selecting the @{b}?@{ub} gadget and then clicking on the spell you wish to
know about.  Or simply by pointing the mouse at the spell in question
and then pressing the @{b}q@{ub} or @{b}?@{ub} key on the keyboard.

   A wizard can decide not to choose a spell by clicking the return
gadget, whence control will pass to the next wizard.

   Assuming you wish to pick a spell, simply click on the desired spell.
During the casting stage you will attempt to use your selected spell.
Care should be taken in spell selection. Consider such things as the
range of the spell, the situation of the wizard, your position on the
board, and whether line of sight is required for the spell. Just press
@{b}c@{ub} (for Casting possibilities) while the mouse is over a spell and
all the possible places that you could cast that spell will be
highlighted on the board.

   Once selected, a spell must be attempted. If the spell is aborted,
it will still be considered used and will not appear on your spell list
in the next round.

   If @{b}Texas Trash'em@{ub} was selected then you will also be required to
select a spell to be discarded (unless you have less than six spells
remaining). Such a selection must be made even if you choose not to
select a spell for casting.


@EndNode

@Node "SpellCasting" "Chaos.Guide/SpellCasting"
@Next "BoardUpdate"
@Prev "SpellSelection"
@Toc "TheGame"

Spell casting
=============

   During spell casting, each player who selected a spell during the
spell selection stage will in turn get a chance to actuate the spell.
Computer controlled wizards will attempt to cast a spell at their
position in the sequence. In addition, each generator on the screen
might produce a creature. Certain other creatures also occasionally
cast spells.

   For each player in turn the spell selected is shown on the bottom
line of the screen, together with the number of attempts and the range
for the spell. For example,

     Gray Elf x1  Range=2

   means 1 Gray Elf is being cast, and the elf can be cast either
immediately adjacent to the wizard or one cell removed from the wizard
(just press @{b}c@{ub} to see all possible legal cells). A range of zero means
the spell can be cast simply by pressing the left mouse button and
there is no need to select a cell. Such spells are often special powers
for the wizard. The computer automatically applies the spell to the
correct wizard or creature.  Certain spells have a range of 15, these
spells can be cast on any appropriate cell on the screen and do not
require line of sight.

   Most spells have a fixed range, measured in a straight line from the
casting wizard. For instance, nearly all creatures have a range of one
and so can only be cast immediately adjacent to the wizard. All these
spells require line of sight. The line of sight is measured from the
centre of the wizard's cell to the centre of the destination cell. You
can see over blank space, dead creatures, pits, pools, and fires.
Sometimes line of sight can be obtained by waiting until an appropriate
time in the animation sequence.(1) By pressing @{b}c@{ub} you can ask the
computer to show you all legal target cells.

   Spells can be aborted by pressing the right mouse button. Aborted
spells still get used up, so try to avoid having to abort spells. If
you find yourself aborting spells often, you are probably not choosing
spells appropriate to your situation.

   Most spells can be cast only on certain types of cell (the program
will notify you of any errors you make in selecting the cell). If you
make an error you are free to choose a new cell. For instance,
creatures can be cast on empty cells or cells containing dead
creatures, but cannot be cast on other creatures or inanimate objects.

   After each wizard has cast, the generators may produce creatures on
any cell adjacent to the generator which is empty, or contains a dead
creature.  Adjacent cells occupied by creatures or inanimate objects
will never be generated upon.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  To experienced players this is known as @{i}forcing@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "BoardUpdate" "Chaos.Guide/BoardUpdate"
@Next "Movement"
@Prev "SpellCasting"
@Toc "TheGame"

Board update
============

   The board update is handled entirely by the computer. The update
carries out activities which are not directly under any player's
control. During the update any or all of the following things might
happen:

   @{b}*@{ub} The growths (earthquakes, fire, flood, fungi, orange jelly, gooey
     blob, and green ooze) are permitted to grow. Each cell containing
     a growth may or may not grow. If a cell is going to grow it will
     do so in only one direction in any particular turn. The direction
     of growth is chosen at random.  Earthquakes cannot "grow"
     diagonally. Some of the growths grow faster than others, orange
     jelly is particularly voracious while floods tend to be sluggish.
     If a cell doesn't grow it might dissipate instead. You may have
     some of your creatures buried, killed, or revealed in this growth
     process.  Should your wizard be buried or killed you are
     considered dead and your game ends (an exception occurs in the
     case of a wizard having previously cast Lich Lord).

     Any creature which is covered by a growth will have its life set
     to one half of its normal maximum upon being uncovered. If the
     growth is killed somehow, such as you shooting it with a bow, then
     all the other stats are left untouched.But if the growth has died
     of natural causes then @{i}all@{ui} the creature's stats will be set to
     their normal intial values, though life will still be cut in half.
     These effects can be exploited by clever players.

     Neither case applies to dead bodies, scrolls or artifact
     creatures. Thus you cannot morph an artifact creature into a non
     artifact creature by letting it get covered up with a growth.

   @{b}*@{ub} Any tempests on the board may move. A creature in the path of the
     tempest will be thrown to a new random location. On very rare
     occasions a creature will be killed as a result of the throw.

   @{b}*@{ub} Any vortices may move. A creature in its path will disappear into
     the future.

   @{b}*@{ub} Ropers get tired of constantly sitting in the same place.
     Sometimes they decide to teleport to a new location.

   @{b}*@{ub} There is a chance that each magic castle, dark citadel or dark
     city on the board might collapse. If a wizard is inside the castle
     or citadel when the collapse occurs the wizard will be granted a
     bonus spell.

   @{b}*@{ub} Any magic wood occupied by a wizard might collapse, resulting in a
     new spell for the wizard.

   @{b}*@{ub} Each sleeping entity is examined and has a chance of dying or
     collapsing.  The weaker things are the more likely they are to be
     destroyed than the stronger things. The destruction will be
     complete and no trace of the entity will remain.

   @{b}*@{ub} Each Haunt has a small chance of changing sides.

   @{b}*@{ub} Each Spriggan has a small chance of falling asleep.

   @{b}*@{ub} (When impurities are turned on) With a small probability an object
     might decide to change sides. This may work to your advantage or
     disadvantage. It is even possible that a generator will become
     your friend and decide to emit creatures for you.


@EndNode

@Node "Movement" "Chaos.Guide/Movement"
@Next "Scoring"
@Prev "BoardUpdate"
@Toc "TheGame"

Movement
========

   The movement stage is the most complex stage, since normally there
are a large number of creatures to be moved and each creature has a
number of possible moves. Each player is given a chance to move in turn
(unless he is the victim of a Freeze spell). The strategies employed
during the movement stage will have the greatest effect on your
survival in the game. Movement involves not only the shifting of
creature positions but also combat.

   Dead creatures, sleeping creatures, and growths cannot be moved. No
inanimates can be moved, although shadow wood trees and bolters may be
used to attack enemy creatures(1) in adjacent cells. Special objects
like ropers, wasp nests or solars are controlled by the computer.

   A player is able to move each creation once in each turn. To end
your turn click on the return gadget and control will pass to the next
player.  Players having cast the Move It spell in the current round
will get a second chance to move after all other players have moved,
but before the independents move.

   A creature is said to be @{i}engaged@{ui} if it is adjacent to an enemy
creature and is unable to retreat. Engaged creatures cannot be moved but
may still be able to fight. How likely a creature is to be engaged is
dependent on its manoeuvrability and the number of adjacent hostile
creatures.

   To move a creature simply click on the creature using the left mouse
button. Normally, the distance the creature may be moved will be
displayed in the text bar. Depending on the creature, it will be flying
movement or walking movement. There is a special cursor when flying
movement is active.  To see all legal moves press the @{b}m@{ub} key.

   For more information, please select:


 @{" Flying movement " Link "FlyingMovement"}               
 @{" Aerial attacks " Link "AerialAttacks"}              
 @{" Walking movement " Link "WalkingMovement"}                
 @{" Combat " Link "Combatting"}           
 @{" Ranged combat " Link "RangedCombat"}             
 @{" Wizard movement " Link "WizardMovement"}               
 @{" Ending your turn " Link "EndingYourTurn"} 

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Unlike creatures, most trees cannot attack other inanimate
objects, or growths


@EndNode

@Node "FlyingMovement" "Chaos.Guide/FlyingMovement"
@Next "AerialAttacks"
@Prev "Movement"
@Toc "Movement"

Flying movement
---------------

   For flying creatures you can pick any cell within the given range
except cells occupied by your team's creations. If the cell is empty or
contains a dead creature then the creature will move to the selected
cell, otherwise an aerial attack will be made on the selected cell.

   The Fly spell is able to provide any creature with wings, however its
movement points won't be altered. The Wizard wings spell gives the
wizard the ability to fly in the range of an eagle.

   Flying movement can be temporarily impossible in the world if the
gravity sphere has been cast, or permanently for a creature if it is
the victim of a singular or dual earthbind spell.


@EndNode

@Node "AerialAttacks" "Chaos.Guide/AerialAttacks"
@Next "WalkingMovement"
@Prev "FlyingMovement"
@Toc "Movement"

Aerial attacks
--------------

   An aerial attack results when a flying creature is moved onto a cell
occupied by an opponent. The flier will attack the current occupant. If
unsuccessful the attacker will remain at its current location. If
successful the current occupant will die and the flying creature will be
moved into the cell.


@EndNode

@Node "WalkingMovement" "Chaos.Guide/WalkingMovement"
@Next "Combatting"
@Prev "AerialAttacks"
@Toc "Movement"

Walking movement
----------------

   A ground based creature can only move one cell at a time and you
must show the computer exactly how to move multiple cells by clicking
in each cell in turn. Many walking creatures can only move one cell
anyway. For those which can move more than one cell you should select a
sequence of adjacent cells -- you can abort the move at any time by
pressing the right mouse button.  During the course of a move a
creature may become engaged in which case it will move no further.


@EndNode

@Node "Combatting" "Chaos.Guide/Combatting"
@Next "RangedCombat"
@Prev "WalkingMovement"
@Toc "Movement"

Combat
------

   Engaged creatures can take part in combat. You cannot attack your
team's creatures (but see @{"RangedCombat" Link "RangedCombat"}), unless the creature currently
moving has a negative combat ability, meaning the attack will actually
heal.  Living creatures cannot (normally) attack undead creatures,
otherwise anything goes. Once engaged, an attack is induced by clicking
on the cell containing the creature you wish to attack. If successful,
the defendant will be killed and the attacker will move onto the
corpse. For a successful kill of a strong opponent you may be awarded a
bonus spell.

   It is possible to attack inanimate objects and growths, although you
cannot get engaged to them. Be wary of killing growths with buried
creatures beneath, as the buried creature will be revealed and will
probably be quite hungry.


@EndNode

@Node "RangedCombat" "Chaos.Guide/RangedCombat"
@Next "WizardMovement"
@Prev "Combatting"
@Toc "Movement"

Ranged combat
-------------

   Some creatures such as elves, dragons, and wizards carrying bows,
have additional attacks. Such an attack is indicated by the @{i}sights
pointer@{ui}. Line of sight is required for most of these weapons. It is
possible to shoot your own creations or creations of your team members,
so choose your targets carefully. Occasionally it might be desirable to
kill one your own creatures due to insanity or disease (especially if
you are playing for points).

   Creatures which posess the @{i}archery@{ui} skill (such as the Wood Elf and
Gray Elf) do not need line of sight to shoot a target. Their shots
simply arch over any intervening obstacles. The Archery spell can give
the archery skill to creatures with some ranged combat ability, while
the Archerotomy will remove this skill.


@EndNode

@Node "WizardMovement" "Chaos.Guide/WizardMovement"
@Next "EndingYourTurn"
@Prev "RangedCombat"
@Toc "Movement"

Wizard movement
---------------

   Under normal circumstances the wizard can be moved like any other
creature.  However, wizards are capable of special movements. Wizards
can climb magic trees, enter castles, and ride certain creatures. For
convenience these activities are collectively called @{i}mounting@{ui}. You
cannot mount if you are engaged, otherwise mounting is effected by
simply moving the wizard onto the cell occupied by the entity you wish
to mount.

   Dismounting is somewhat more complicated as the computer needs to
distinguish which of the two entities is to be moved. For trees and
castles the computer will assume the wizard. For ridden creatures the
default is the creature. To dismount from a creature the following
sequence should occur:

   @{b}*@{ub} Select the creature the wizard is riding.

   @{b}*@{ub} Click on the `D' gadget at the top right of the screen (which will
     now be unghosted).

   @{b}*@{ub} Move the wizard to a cell adjacent to the creature (wizards with
     high movement allowance or wings still only move one cell when
     dismounting).

   Mounting is generally a good idea, as it hides the wizard from view
and gives the wizard additional protection.


@EndNode

@Node "EndingYourTurn" "Chaos.Guide/EndingYourTurn"
@Next "Scoring"
@Prev "WizardMovement"
@Toc "Movement"

Ending your turn
----------------

   Once you have moved all creatures that you wish to, select the end
of turn gadget. Computer controlled wizards will move their creations
at the appropriate point in the sequence. After all wizards have moved
the independent creatures will be moved by the computer according to
the same rules.

   Finally, any wasp nests, ropers, fungi and anything else that has the
Special Combat Attribute will attack adjacent opponents.

   Note that some objects such as Pools, Apple Wood Trees, Hippocrates
and others have @{i}negative@{ui} special combat. This means their Special Combat
actually heals those that it attacks.

   The round is now effectively over and the game returns to the spell
selection stage for the next round.


@EndNode

@Node "Scoring" "Chaos.Guide/Scoring"
@Next "Information"
@Prev "Movement"
@Toc "TheGame"

Scoring
=======

   The computer keeps track of a score for each player and this is
indicated by the computer displaying a ranking of all wizards and the
independents at the end of the game. There is a score and a life
column. The life column is the sum of the life force of a wizard's
creations excepting walls, castles, and certain other inanimate
objects. The current scores can be examined during the spell selection
stage using the menus.

   Points are awarded for killing enemy creatures and wizards. The
stronger the creatures you kill the more points you get. Bonus spells
are awarded for killing particularly strong creatures. Points are also
awarded for successfully casting some difficult or unusual spells.
Points are even awarded for destroying or burying corpses.


@EndNode

@Node "Information" "Chaos.Guide/Information"
@Next "Keys"
@Prev "Scoring"
@Toc "TheGame"

Information
===========

   The @{b}?@{ub} gadget can be used to get information about objects on the
board (at any time) and about spells (during spell selection). For an
object on the screen, a window is displayed showing various
characteristics of the chosen object. The @{b}?@{ub} gadget will not reveal any
useful information when applied to a cloaked creature, unless you own
it.

   The information screen for a wizard or a cell containing a mounted
wizard will also display the various power-ups held by the wizard as
icons.

   Most creature's Combat stats affect their opponent's Life stat but
Some creatures, like the Mind Flayer, attack Intelligence or some other
stat.  Sometimes a creature's Combat or Ranged Combat or Special Combat
will affect more than one of your Enemy's stats at a time.

   Just press the Left Mouse button on either Combat, Ranged Combat or
Special Combat and all the stats that it attacks will begin flashing.

   For more details please select:


 @{" Objects statistics " Link "ObjectsStatistics"}                  
 @{" Spell information " Link "SpellInformation"} 


@EndNode

@Node "ObjectsStatistics" "Chaos.Guide/ObjectsStatistics"
@Next "SpellInformation"
@Prev "Information"
@Toc "Information"

Objects statistics
------------------

   Each object in the game, be it a creature, wizard, generator, scroll
or whatever, has a certain number of characteristics which determine its
appearance, properties, abilities and behavior in the game. Some of them
are shown on the information panels when the @{b}?@{ub} gadget is used (except
if the object is a scroll, then the spell description is shown), some
are hidden. Some may be affected in the game by spells or certain forms
of combat, some are invariable.

   This section explains the use and meaning of @{i}some@{ui} of those
characteristics.


 @{" Identity " Link "IdentityStat"}             
 @{" Class " Link "ClassStat"}          
 @{" Ownership " Link "OwnershipStat"}              
 @{" Team " Link "TeamStat"}         
 @{" Life status " Link "LifeStatusStat"}               
 @{" Movement type " Link "MovementTypeStat"}                 
 @{" Mountability " Link "MountabilityStat"}                 
 @{" Meditation " Link "MeditationStat"}               
 @{" Action on line of sight " Link "ActionOnLineOfSightStat"}                        
 @{" Possible opponents " Link "PossibleOpponentsStat"}                      
 @{" Archery " Link "ArcheryStat"}            
 @{" Exophagy " Link "ExophagyStat"}             
 @{" Foes vainquished " Link "FoesVainquishedStat"}                    
 @{" Life force " Link "LifeForceStat"}              
 @{" Magical resistance " Link "MagicalResistanceStat"}                      
 @{" Manoeuvrability " Link "ManoeuvrabilityStat"}                    
 @{" Intelligence " Link "IntelligenceStat"}                 
 @{" Combat " Link "CombatStat"}           
 @{" Ranged combat " Link "RangedCombatStat"}                 
 @{" Special combat " Link "SpecialCombatStat"}                  
 @{" Movement " Link "MovementStat"}             
 @{" Range " Link "RangeStat"}          
 @{" Scavengerism " Link "ScavengerismStat"}                 
 @{" Special capabilities " Link "SpecialCapabilitiesStat"} 


@EndNode

@Node "IdentityStat" "Chaos.Guide/IdentityStat"
@Next "ClassStat"
@Prev "ObjectsStatistics"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Identity
........

   This characteristic uniquely determines what the object is in the
game. It can be a particular creature or a particular inanimate object
(like a bipedal generator). This also determines the @{i}initial@{ui} value of
all other characteristics. When this object gets hit with the
Restoration spell, all its characteristics revert to their initial
values, including those affected by combat and/or magic. There are a
few spells, like alter reality, which will turn a particular object
into another.


@EndNode

@Node "ClassStat" "Chaos.Guide/ClassStat"
@Next "OwnershipStat"
@Prev "IdentityStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Class
.....

   This determines if the object is a creature, a growth, an inanimate
object, a scroll or an artifact. There are spells in the game which can
make an object change its class. Among them are: Stone to Flesh, Flesh
to Stone and Mass Morph.


@EndNode

@Node "OwnershipStat" "Chaos.Guide/OwnershipStat"
@Next "TeamStat"
@Prev "ClassStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Ownership
.........

   This statistic indicates "who" has "control" over this object (these
words have to be taken in a very general sense since sometimes no
control is performed at all). This can be any living (or sometimes
dead) player, the independents, the sleeping creatures, the dead or
nobody. Of course there are numerous spells which can make a creature
change its ownership: Subversion, Betrayal, Charm and Sleep are some of
them.


@EndNode

@Node "TeamStat" "Chaos.Guide/TeamStat"
@Next "LifeStatusStat"
@Prev "OwnershipStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Team
....

   This is more a consequence of the ownership. It is determined by the
team the controlling wizard is in; as a consequence of the team
settings at the beginning of the game or of the Alliance/Separation
spells. This is of importance since a creature cannot attack its allies
by direct combat.


@EndNode

@Node "LifeStatusStat" "Chaos.Guide/LifeStatusStat"
@Next "MovementTypeStat"
@Prev "TeamStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Life status
...........

   Objects in the game can be living or undead. Generally, living
creatures cannot attack the undead, though there are numerous
exceptions such as the Imp, The Exorcist or any Wizard with a magic
weapon. Some spells can flip this life status (like Lich and Convert),
some spells affect only the living, others only the undead.  Certain
spells, such as Exorcise, can only be cast on an undead target.


@EndNode

@Node "MovementTypeStat" "Chaos.Guide/MovementTypeStat"
@Next "MountabilityStat"
@Prev "LifeStatusStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Movement type
.............

   In the game creatures can move by flying or staying on the ground.
This statistic, which only makes sense for creatures, detemines the
type of movement for a particular object. Flying movement enables
special features like the ability to mount aerial attacks or, for most
flying creatures, the ability to see and map the world without need for
line of sight. Depending on the scroll rules setting, flying creatures
may however be unable to pick up srolls. Some spells exist that affect
the movement type, among them are Fly, Singular Earthbind and Dual
Earthbind.


@EndNode

@Node "MountabilityStat" "Chaos.Guide/MountabilityStat"
@Next "MeditationStat"
@Prev "MovementTypeStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Mountability
............

   This particular statistic indicates whether the wizard is able to
mount the object or not.  It can take three values:  either the object
is non-mountable, a mountable set 1 or mountable set 2.  Objects which
are mountable set 1 can be directly ridden by the wizard.  They range
from the Horse and Pegasus to the Magic Wood and the Shadow City.
Objects which are mountable set 2 can only be ridden by the wizard
after he has cast the Ride spell, as mounting them requires more
training.  They include all dragons, the hardy Elephant, the swift Bird
Lord and even the fearsome Tyrannasaurus Rex.  The mountability
statistic can be affected by the Mount and No Mount spells.


@EndNode

@Node "MeditationStat" "Chaos.Guide/MeditationStat"
@Next "ActionOnLineOfSightStat"
@Prev "MountabilityStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Meditation
..........

   Some mountable objects provide a meditation place for the wizard.
When the wizard enters a meditation object, there is a chance on each
turn during board update that the object collapses. If this happens,
the wizard is granted a bonus spell. This is the case for some trees
and various types of castles, specifically: Magic Wood, Castle, Dark
Citadel, and Shadow City.


@EndNode

@Node "ActionOnLineOfSightStat" "Chaos.Guide/ActionOnLineOfSightStat"
@Next "PossibleOpponentsStat"
@Prev "MeditationStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Action on line of sight
.......................

   Most objects in the game block line of sight for everybody, with
consequences on mapping the world, casting spells and ranged combat.
However, there exist certain objects which don't block line of sight at
all, like corpses or earthquakes.  This is determined by this statistic,
which can have another value indicating it blocks only enemies' line of
sight.  This usually involves some kind of magic, like the Magic Glass
or cloaked creatures.


@EndNode

@Node "PossibleOpponentsStat" "Chaos.Guide/PossibleOpponentsStat"
@Next "ArcheryStat"
@Prev "ActionOnLineOfSightStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Possible opponents
..................

   This statistic can take four values.  Either the object is able to
attack only living objects, only the undead, both or none.  Usually,
living creatures cannot attack the undead but there are exceptions like
the Arctic Wolf and Iridium Horse.  Undeads can usually attack both the
living and the undead.  The Confidence spell, Sword of Sassenrath and
Cursed Sword can be used to alter this particular statistic.


@EndNode

@Node "ArcheryStat" "Chaos.Guide/ArcheryStat"
@Next "ExophagyStat"
@Prev "PossibleOpponentsStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Archery
.......

   For an object capable of ranged combat, this statistic states if
line of sight is needed to shoot a target or not. All elves have this
archery skill. The Archery spell can provide it to a creature which
does not possess it.  The Archerotomy spell can remove it from a
creature which already has it.


@EndNode

@Node "ExophagyStat" "Chaos.Guide/ExophagyStat"
@Next "FoesVainquishedStat"
@Prev "ArcheryStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Exophagy
........

   When this attribute is on, it means that this creature will be able
to eat its opponent alive.  Half of the damage inflicted by this
creature in hand-to-hand combat is added to its life force.  Prime
examples of exophagists are the Vampire and the Neo-Otyugh.  This
attribute can be set by the Exophagy spell.


@EndNode

@Node "FoesVainquishedStat" "Chaos.Guide/FoesVainquishedStat"
@Next "LifeForceStat"
@Prev "ExophagyStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Foes vainquished
................

   This is the list of all objects that were killed by this creature.
Depending on the identity of the objects, some powerups are possible.
For example, a green dragon which successfully gets seven kills becomes
an Emerald Dragon, which is much more powerful.


@EndNode

@Node "LifeForceStat" "Chaos.Guide/LifeForceStat"
@Next "MagicalResistanceStat"
@Prev "FoesVainquishedStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Life force
..........

   Life Force is also known as "hit points".  This very important
characteristic determines the resistance of the object to physical
damage by combat, ranged combat, special combat, magic and poison.  If
the life force of an object becomes negative the object dies.  Normally
if the life force becomes 0, the object dies.  However, death by poison
requires that the life force drop to below 0 before death occurs.  The
life force of a corpse begins at 0 and is lowered when a scavenger eats
some of it.  When a corpse's life force reaches the negative of its
normal maximum, it is considered consumed and disappears from play.  A
recovery rate from -7 to 7 is available on each turn:  auto-healing
capabilities (when positive) or poison (when negative).  The Armor
spell can be used to raise the life force of a creature, and it can be
lowered by numerous other means.  Other spells or forms of combat (like
the bite of the Giant Rat) affect the recovery ability.


@EndNode

@Node "MagicalResistanceStat" "Chaos.Guide/MagicalResistanceStat"
@Next "ManoeuvrabilityStat"
@Prev "LifeForceStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Magical resistance
..................

   All creatures are not equal when it comes to magic. Some are very
vulnerable to magic spells whereas others (not necessarily those which
are physically resistant) can show a very strong aptitude to resist
magical attacks. Usually a creature dies when its magical resistance,
which normally ranges from 0 to 7, becomes negative.  Certain
ultra-powerful spells such as Justice, Dark Power and Exorcism kill the
creature if they lower the magic resistance to 0.

   A recover rate from -7 to 7 is possible. The magical resistance of a
particular creature can be raised by the magic shield spell, which can
also be used to improve the recovery rate for magical resistance. The
spells which attack the magical resistance are many, and there are also
creatures which attack it like the Juju Zombie.


@EndNode

@Node "ManoeuvrabilityStat" "Chaos.Guide/ManoeuvrabilityStat"
@Next "IntelligenceStat"
@Prev "MagicalResistanceStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Manoeuvrability
...............

   Ranging from 0 to 15 with a maximum recovery of 7, this
characteristic (also called agility) determines the probability that
the creature gets engaged at the beginning of its movement phase when
an enemy is adjacent.  Creatures whose manoeuvrability is 0 are always
engaged while those whose manoeuvrability is 15 are never engaged and
can always escape a battle.  All creatures immediately become engaged
upon moving next to any enemy creature, regardless of their agility
rating.  The Command spell can be used to raise the agility of all the
creations of the casting wizard.  The Spectator, Python and a few other
creatures attack this statistic.


@EndNode

@Node "IntelligenceStat" "Chaos.Guide/IntelligenceStat"
@Next "CombatStat"
@Prev "ManoeuvrabilityStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Intelligence
............

   The intelligence or stupidity of a creature in Chaos is measured
from 0 (very stupid) to 15 (most intelligent), with a recovery rate
from -7 to 7.  When the intelligence of a creature becomes negative, it
dies as the synaptic damage prevents its brain from maintaining its own
vital functions.  Intelligence can be raised by the Brain Boost spell
or lowered with the Brain Drain spell, among others. This
characteristic also determines the probability of success of
Subversion-like spells on the creature.  Certain creatures, such as the
Mind Flayer, attack this statistic.


@EndNode

@Node "CombatStat" "Chaos.Guide/CombatStat"
@Next "RangedCombatStat"
@Prev "IntelligenceStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Combat
......

   One of the most important statistics, combat reflects the ability of
a particular creature to cause damage to other objects in the world.
Possible values range from -15 to 15 with a recovery rate from -7 to 7.
Each time the creature attacks another object, its combat statistic is
subtracted from the target statistics of the attacked creature.  If the
combat statistic is negative, this means that the attack will in fact
heal the targetted creature (which can be an ally or an enemy).
However, creatures with positive combat cannot attack their allies.
This prevents simple mistakes of accidentally clicking on a friendly
creature and wounding it.  A variety of characteristics can be altered
by combat.  Usually this will be the life force but, for example, the
Arctic Wolf attacks simultaneously the life force, manoeuvrability and
movement points.  The combat ability can be magically raised for
example by the Combat spell, destroyed with Demonic Touch, or the
target statistic changed by the Poison Dagger spell.


@EndNode

@Node "RangedCombatStat" "Chaos.Guide/RangedCombatStat"
@Next "SpecialCombatStat"
@Prev "CombatStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Ranged combat
.............

   Some creatures have the ability to shoot missiles, such as arrows or
fire breath (like Red Dragons). This is indicated by a positive (from 1
to 15) ranged combat ability, which will be subtracted from the target
statistics of the targetted creature. A negative ranged combat ability
means ranged healing. This statistic can be magically altered by the
Range Boost spell or the Range Drain Beam. However, there is no direct
way to produce a generic creature which has no initial ranged combat
ability with this capacity. The wizard, however, can make use of the
Magic Bow and protect himself with the Reflector spell. A recovery rate
from -7 to 7 is possible.


@EndNode

@Node "SpecialCombatStat" "Chaos.Guide/SpecialCombatStat"
@Next "MovementStat"
@Prev "RangedCombatStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Special combat
..............

   This very special capability ranging from -15 to 15 is like combat
in that it attacks some characteristics of other creatures, but differs
in the way it is done. Special combat takes place after the movement
phase and possibly affects every surrounding object. It can also affect
allies as well as enemies, depending on the object possessing special
combat. Any creature can be given special combat through the Shocker
spell and there is almost no way to ever remove it. A recovery rate
ranging from -7 to 7 is possible.


@EndNode

@Node "MovementStat" "Chaos.Guide/MovementStat"
@Next "RangeStat"
@Prev "SpecialCombatStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Movement
........

   This statistic determines how far a creature can move during the
movement phase. This can however be limited by engagement in battles.
Any creature can be sped up with the Speed spell or slowed by the Slow
spell, among several other spells. Some creatures also attack this
rating, such as the Basilisk. Unfortunately there is no recovery
statistic for movement.


@EndNode

@Node "RangeStat" "Chaos.Guide/RangeStat"
@Next "ScavengerismStat"
@Prev "MovementStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Range
.....

   This statistic tells how many cells away the creature can shoot with
ranged combat. This is altered by the Range Boost and Range Drain Beam
spells.


@EndNode

@Node "ScavengerismStat" "Chaos.Guide/ScavengerismStat"
@Next "SpecialCapabilitiesStat"
@Prev "RangeStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

Scavengerism
............

   This important capability of a particular creature enables it to
feed on corpses. On each turn, the creature is able to eat as many life
points from the corpse it's standing on as its scavengerism statistic
and add them to its own life force. When the life force of the corpse
reaches the negative of its initial value, the corpse is fully consumed
and disappears.  Some creatures such as the Dire Wolf, Arctic Wolf,
Vulture and Neo-Otyugh (among others) always have this statistic.
However, most creatures can only scavenge after being the recipient of
the Scavengerism spell.

Special capabilities
....................


@EndNode

@Node "SpecialCapabilitiesStat" "Chaos.Guide/SpecialCapabilitiesStat"
@Next "SpellInformation"
@Prev "ScavengerismStat"
@Toc "ObjectsStatistics"

   Under this term are grouped some attributes which can only be
granted by magic. This includes the effect of the Horror spell, or the
number of reincarnations left, when the creature was hit by the
Reincarnate spell.  The wizard itself has many more possible powerups
than any other creature.


@EndNode

@Node "SpellInformation" "Chaos.Guide/SpellInformation"
@Next "Keys"
@Prev "ObjectsStatistics"
@Toc "Information"

Spell information
-----------------

   Like the objects in the world, the available spells have a certain
number of characteristics which have to be taken into account when
choosing the spell and the target. @{i}Some@{ui} of these rules can be read by
clicking on the @{b}?@{ub} gadget then on the icon of the spell to read about.
Or you can just press "q" on the keyboard while the mousepointer is
pointing at any spell or scroll.  "q" stands for "query" or "question
mark".

   This works on any spell in the casting wizard's spell list or any
scroll on the board.  With the right magic item it can even work on
enemy wizard's spell lists!


 @{" Spell name " Link "SpellNameStat"}              
 @{" Probability " Link "SpellProbabilityStat"}                     
 @{" Spell range " Link "SpellRangeStat"}               
 @{" Multiplicity " Link "SpellMultiplicityStat"}                      
